{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20161213012609|754508580","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Todd_Rokita","to":"Todd Rokita"}],"pages":{"4146159":{"pageid":4146159,"ns":0,"title":"Todd Rokita","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2016-12-24T18:51:37Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Todd Rokita\n|image        = Todd Rokita, Official Portrait, 112th Congress.jpg\n|state        = [[Indiana]]\n|district     = {{ushr|IN|4|4th}}\n|term_start   = January 3, 2011\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Steve Buyer]]\n|successor    = \n|office1      = [[Secretary of State of Indiana]]\n|governor1    = [[Frank O'Bannon]]<br>[[Joe E. Kernan|Joe Kernan]]<br>[[Mitch Daniels]]\n|term_start1  = December 1, 2002\n|term_end1    = December 1, 2010\n|predecessor1 = [[Sue Anne Gilroy|Sue Gilroy]]\n|successor1   = [[Charles P. White|Charlie White]]\n|birth_name   = Theodore Edward Rokita\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1970|2|9}}\n|birth_place  = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Kathy Rokita\n|children     = 2\n|alma_mater   = [[Wabash College]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>{{nowrap|[[Indiana University \u2013 Purdue University Indianapolis|Indiana University, Indianapolis]]}} {{small|([[Juris Doctor|JD]])}}\n|website      = {{url|rokita.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Theodore Edward \"Todd\" Rokita''' (born February 9, 1970) is an [[United States|American]] politician who has been a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from {{ushr|IN|4}} since 2011. Rokita, a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], previously served two terms as [[Secretary of State of Indiana]] from 2002 to 2010. When Rokita was elected to office in 2002 at the age of 32, he became at the time the youngest [[Secretary of State (U.S. state government)|secretary of state]] in the [[United States]].\n\nHe was a candidate to replace [[Mike Pence]] in the [[Indiana gubernatorial election, 2016|2016 Indiana gubernatorial election]] after Pence withdrew from the race to be [[Donald Trump]]'s running mate in the [[United States Presidential election, 2016|2016 U.S. Presidential election]].  However, Indiana Republicans went on to select [[Eric Holcomb]], Indiana's current Lieutenant Governor and Pence's second in command during his administration.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/27/us/indiana-governor-mike-pence.html|title=Indiana Governor Mike Pence|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education and career==\nRokita grew up in [[Munster, Indiana|Munster]], located in [[Lake County, Indiana|Lake County]] in [[Northwest Indiana]]. Rokita attended [[Munster High School]].<ref name=\"Franklin\">{{cite web | url=http://www.nwitimes.com/news/local/lake/munster/munster-speech-team-takes-top-state-honors-for-lucky-th/article_f446a3fe-f6ab-5890-8d6d-6f7cf23c53eb.html | title=Munster speech team takes top state honors for lucky 13th time | date=17 May 2012 | accessdate=17 January 2014 | author=Franklin, Lu Ann}}</ref> He holds a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree from [[Wabash College]] in [[Crawfordsville, Indiana]], where he was an [[Eli Lilly and Company|Eli Lilly]] Fellow. He is a member of the [[Sigma Chi]] fraternity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weblinks.sigmachi.org/preview/marketing/PAC/list.pdf |format=PDF |title=Sigma Chi Candidates for the U.S. Congress 2010 |website=Weblinks.sigmachi.org |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref> He has a law degree from [[Indiana University Robert H. McKinney School of Law]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=R000592 |title=ROKITA, Todd \u2013 Biographical Information |publisher=Bioguide.congress.gov |date= |accessdate=2013-10-21}}</ref>\n\nRokita was a practicing attorney. In 1997 he joined the secretary of state's office as general counsel. He later became deputy secretary of state.<ref name=\"vote-in.org\">{{cite web|url=http://vote-in.org/Intro.aspx?State=IN&Id=INRokitaTodd |title=Vote In biographical profile of Todd Rokita |publisher=Vote-in.org |date= |accessdate=2013-10-21}}</ref>\n\n==Indiana Secretary of State==\nRokita was elected by his peers nationally to serve on the nine-member federal executive board of the Election Assistance Commission.<ref name=\"vote-in.org\" /> The commission is charged by law to address election reform issues on a nationwide basis. Rokita has testified about Indiana's voting reform efforts before the United States Congress.\n\nAs secretary of state, Rokita visited each of Indiana's ninety-two counties at least once per year. Rokita was named as one of the \"40 under 40\" by the ''Indianapolis Business Journal''.{{When|date=April 2011}} Rokita was active in the [[National Association of Secretaries of State]] (NASS), and after serving as the elected treasurer, he became the President for the 2007\u20132008 term.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.insideindianabusiness.com/newsitem.asp?ID=24474 |title=Rokita Becomes President of National Association of Secretaries of State \u2013 Newsroom \u2013 Inside INdiana Business with Gerry Dick |publisher=Insideindianabusiness.com |date=2007-07-18 |accessdate=2010-08-23}}</ref>\n\nRokita was a named defendant in the Hoosier State's voter identification case went before the [[U.S. Supreme Court]] on January 9, 2008; the combined cases of ''[[Crawford v. Marion County Election Board]]'' (07-21) and ''[[Indiana Democratic Party v. Rokita]]'' (07-25) involved the Indiana voting requirement laws that require voters display state-issued photo IDs before voting. In April 2008, the US Supreme Court upheld that law. Rokita also served as Indiana's chief [[securities fraud]] investigator.\n\nIn September 2009, Rokita outlined a plan to reform how Indiana's legislative districts are drawn to reduce [[gerrymandering]]. He proposed making it a felony for lawmakers to use political data or incumbents' addresses when drawing electoral maps. [[Indiana's congressional districts]] and districts for the [[Indiana Senate]] and [[Indiana House of Representatives]] will next be redrawn after the [[2010 United States Census|2010 Census]]. Rokita says boundaries should follow existing county and township lines, and that each of the 50 senate districts should be divided into two house districts, claiming this will lead to more competitive legislative elections.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indystar.com/article/20090908/NEWS05/909080333/Lawmakers+draw+line+at+redistricting+plan|title=Lawmakers draw a line at Rokita's redistricting plan|last=Schneider|first=Mary Beth |date=September 8, 2009|work=The Indianapolis Star|accessdate=2009-09-08}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on the Budget|Committee on the Budget]]'''\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Education and the Workforce|Committee on Education and the Workforce]]'''\n** [[United States House Education Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Elementary and Secondary Education|Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Elementary and Secondary Education]] (Chairman)\n** [[United States House Education Subcommittee on Workforce Protections|Subcommittee on Workforce Protections]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure]]'''\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Aviation|Subcommittee on Aviation]]\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials|Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials]]\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment|Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment]]\n\nRokita previously served on the [[United States House Committee on House Administration|Committee on House Administration]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/committee_info/scsoal.pdf |format=PDF |title=List of Standing Committees |website=In.gov |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://cha.house.gov/press-release/house-administration-adopts-subcommittee-assignments |title=House Administration Adopts Subcommittee Assignments &#124; Committee on House Administration |website=Cha.house.gov |date=2011-01-25 |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nOn Aug. 4, 2014, on an Indianapolis radio program, while discussing the [[2014 American immigration crisis]], Rokita expressed concerns about the ability of border patrol agents to properly process and screen individuals entering the country illegally.  He stated that \u201cfrom a public-health standpoint\u201d that we \u201cneed to know the condition of these kids\u201d while citing the [[Ebola virus epidemic in West Africa]] as a news event that shows how rapidly diseases can spread.  In response to reports stating that Rokita believed that illegal immigrants could be carrying Ebola, he clarified that \u201cthe sudden spread of Ebola in Africa is merely one example of how we must take deliberate care to prevent an outbreak of any type of disease inside our borders.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://rokita.house.gov/press-release/rokita-response-column-border-crisis |title=Rokita Response to Column on Border Crisis &#124; Congressman Todd Rokita |website=Rokita.house.gov |date=2014-08-05 |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref> Rokita also cited news reports indicating that nationals from 75 different countries had been apprehended between 2010 and 2014 illegally crossing the [[Mexico\u2013United States border]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/93wibc/garrison8-4-final |title=Garrison8 - 4 FINAL by 93WIBC &#124; Free Listening on SoundCloud |website=Soundcloud.com |date=2016-04-29 |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013 during the American government shutdown, Rokita was interviewed by CNN journalist Carol Costello. Her pointed questions about Rokita's defense of the shutdown that furloughed hundreds of thousands of government employees without compensation while he continued to receive his paycheck, were eventually countered with his statement that she was \"beautiful but you have to be honest\" and that journalists were part of the problem.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fung|first=Katherine|title=Rep. Todd Rokita To CNN's Carol Costello: 'You're Beautiful But You Have To Be Honest'|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/10/03/todd-rokita-carol-costello-cnn-beautiful_n_4036782.html|publisher=Huffington Post|accessdate=25 October 2013|date=October 3, 2013}}</ref> The Congressman's office issued a statement that he intended no offense by his comments.\n\nIn April 2007, Rokita was speaking at a Republican event, and encouraged Republicans to reach out to African-Americans. He mentioned 90 percent of [[African Americans]] vote [[U.S. Democratic Party|Democratic]], after which he asked, \"How can that be? Ninety to ten. Who's the master and who's the slave in that relationship? How can that be healthy?\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.idsnews.com/news/NewStoryPrint.aspx?id=54177 | title =Racist remark angers lawmakers Representative: Secretary of State should apologize | author =Alexandra R. Moses, Mike Smith  | author2 =''[[Associated Press]]'' | publisher =''[[Indiana Daily Student]]''}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/politics/todd-rokita-r--20101024 | title =Todd Rokita (R) | author =Brendan Sasso | publisher =nationaljournal.com | date =November 3, 2010}}</ref>  Four days after making those remarks, he apologized.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f%3D%2Fn%2Fa%2F2007%2F04%2F16%2Fnational%2Fa124340D15.DTL%26type%3Dpolitics |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-04-17 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071223072131/http://www.sfgate.com:80/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/n/a/2007/04/16/national/a124340D15.DTL&type=politics |archivedate=2007-12-23 |df= }}</ref> Rokita also met privately with eleven members of the Indiana Black Legislative Caucus to apologize for the comment. Representative [[Vernon Smith (Indiana politician)|Vernon Smith]], D-[[Gary, Indiana|Gary]], told reporters, \u201cHe apologized to our satisfaction. We do believe he was sincere in his apology,\" Smith said. \"I think there are greater issues \u2013 education, health, economics for the black community \u2013 that are more important than us spending all this time on a slip of the lip. I do believe that we all make mistakes (and) that if we expect to be forgiven, we need to forgive.\" During the course of the same private meeting Rokita was told his office should reflect the diversity of the state, at the time of his remarks 89% of the employees in Rokita's office were white.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.theindychannel.com/news/politics/rokita-apologizes-to-black-lawmakers-for-slave-remark |title=Rokita Apologizes To Black Lawmakers For Slave Remark |website=TheIndyChannel.com |date=2007-04-18 |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\n==Political campaigns==\n;2002\n\nOn June 15, 2002, Rokita won the Republican nomination for Indiana Secretary of State in the third round of voting at the state convention.  He won the nomination over [[Mike Delph]], then an aide to U.S. Representative [[Dan Burton]], Marion County Coroner John McGodd, and then-Vanderburgh County Commissioner [[Richard Mourdock]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nwitimes.com/uncategorized/gop-nominates-rokita-at-convention/article_8dc133f9-86e1-53af-bcfd-9951f21de5ab.html |title=GOP nominates Rokita at convention &#124; Uncategorized |website=Nwitimes.com |date=2002-06-15 |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\nRokita went on to win the general election with 53.4% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.in.gov/sos/elections/files/2002_ELECTION_BOOKLET.pdf |format=PDF |title=Election Results : Indiana : 2002 |website=In.gov |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\n;2006\n\nHe received the Republican nomination again in 2006 and won the general election with 51.1% of the vote in a year when Democrats took 5 of Indiana\u2019s 9 Congressional Seats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.in.gov/sos/elections/files/2006_Election_Report.pdf |format=PDF |title=Election Results : Indiana : 2006 |website=In.gov |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\n;2010\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Indiana, 2010#District 4}}\nOn February 1, 2010, three days after Congressman [[Steve Buyer]] of {{ushr|Indiana|4}} said that he would retire at the end of his term, Rokita posted an announcement on [[Facebook]] making clear his intentions to run for the open seat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jconline.com/article/20100202/ELECTION01/2020334|title=Hershman, Rokita among growing field for Buyer's seat|date=February 2, 2010|accessdate=February 2, 2010|work=[[Journal & Courier]]|first=Mary Beth|last=Schneider}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nBuyer's announcement touched off a free-for-all among area Republicans to succeed him.  Ultimately,  thirteen candidates entered the Republican primary, including Rokita.  With a [[Cook Partisan Voting Index]] of R+14, the 4th is one of the most Republican districts in the [[Eastern Time Zone]] and tied for the second-most Republican in the state (behind the 5th District).  It was taken for granted that whoever won the primary would be heavily favored to be the district's next congressman.\n\nRokita won the primary with 42 percent of the vote, and went on to win the general election with 68.6% of the vote.\n\n;2012\n\nRokita won the general election in 2012 with 62% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.in.gov/apps/sos/election/general/general2012?page=office&countyID=-1&officeID=5&districtID=-1&candidate= |title=Election Results : Indiana : 2012 |website=In.gov |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\n;2014\n\nRokita won the Republican nomination in 2014 with 71% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.in.gov/apps/sos/primary/sos_primary14?page=office&countyID=-1&partyID=-1&officeID=5&districtID=-1&districtshortviewID=-1&candidate= |title=Election Results : Indiana : 2014 |website=In.gov |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>  He won the general election with 67% of the vote over John Dale, a teacher at [[Western Boone High School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.in.gov/apps/sos/election/general/general2014?page=office&countyID=-1&officeID=5&districtID=-1&candidate= |title=Election Results : Indiana : 2014 |website=In.gov |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\n;2016\n\nRokita won the Republican nomination in 2016 with 60% of the vote.  He faces John Dale again in the general election.\n\n==Tenure==\n;Agriculture\nRokita is against federal government regulation over farming. A representative of a heavy-farming district in [[Indiana]], Rokita has voted in favor of deregulating farmer restrictions, earning him an \"A\" rating from the American Farm Bureau Federation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/34167/todd-rokita/4 |title=Todd Rokita's Ratings and Endorsements - The Voter's Self Defense System |publisher=Vote Smart |date=2016-05-03 |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref> He co-sponsored the Farm Dust Regulation Prevention Act \u2013 passing the House in March 2011 \u2013 in order to prevent the \"significant burden on small businesses for little obvious environmental benefit.\" Rokita also co-sponsored the Preserving America's Family Farms Act \u2013 which passed the House in July 2012 \u2013 citing Indiana's dependence on youth work on family farms.<ref name=\"toddrokitaforcongress1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.toddrokitaforcongress.com/about.html |title=Todd Rokita for Congress |publisher=Todd Rokita for Congress |date= |accessdate=2013-10-21}}</ref>\n\n;Education\nRokita has been a supporter of charter schools and reducing the role of the [[United States Department of Education|Department of Education]] in setting education policy.<ref>{{cite web|last=Klein |first=Alyson |url=http://blogs.edweek.org/edweek/campaign-k-12/2013/01/conservative_rep_todd_rokita_n.html |title=Conservative Rep. Todd Rokita Named Chairman of K-12 Panel - Politics K-12 - Education Week |website=Blogs.edweek.org |date=2013-01-03 |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>  As Chairman of the Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Elementary, and Secondary Education, he had an active role in crafting the [[Every Student Succeeds Act]], which reauthorized the 1965 [[Elementary and Secondary Education Act]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Alexis Moberger |url=http://wlfi.com/2016/03/13/new-education-law-guts-no-child-left-behind-act/ |title=New education law guts No Child Left Behind Act |website=Wlfi.com |date=2016-03-13 |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Klein |first=Alyson |url=http://blogs.edweek.org/edweek/campaign-k-12/2015/11/_after_more_than_a.html |title=House, Senate ESEA Compromise Sails Through Conference Committee - Politics K-12 - Education Week |website=Blogs.edweek.org |date=2015-11-19 |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\n;Gun Control\nRokita is a strong supporter of the [[Second Amendment to the United States Constitution|Second Amendment]], saying \"I\u2019m proud of my 'A' rating from the [[National Rifle Association|NRA]]. If we are going to keep up our traditions and pass them on to our children, we need leaders in Congress who understand, and will fight every day, to protect our 2nd Amendment right to keep and bear arms.\"<ref name=\"toddrokitaforcongress1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/34167/todd-rokita/37 |title=Todd Rokita's Ratings and Endorsements - The Voter's Self Defense System |publisher=Vote Smart |date=2016-05-03 |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref> Rokita voted in favor of a bill \"Requiring State Reciprocity for Carrying Concealed Firearms\" in November 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/key-votes/34167/todd-rokita/37/gun-issues |title=Todd Rokita's Voting Records on Issue: - The Voter's Self Defense System |publisher=Vote Smart |date= |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\n;Health Care\nRokita opposes any Health Care regulation that increases the national debt, earning a \"B\" rating by the National Taxpayers Union 2011 Positions on Tax and Spending.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/interest-group/872/rating/5941 |title=National Taxpayers Union Rating - The Voter's Self Defense System |publisher=Vote Smart |date= |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref> He opposes the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] and was the key vote to repeal the health care law and health care-related provisions in the Health Care and Education Reconciliation Act of 2010.<ref>[http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c112:hr2 ]{{dead link|date=November 2016}}</ref> His healthcare voting record has given him an extremely low approval ratings from care-related interest groups such as the Association of University Centers on Disabilities and the American Nurses Association.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/34167/todd-rokita/38 |title=Todd Rokita's Ratings and Endorsements - The Voter's Self Defense System |publisher=Vote Smart |date= |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\n;Taxes\nIn 2010 Rokita signed a pledge sponsored by [[Americans for Prosperity]] promising to vote against any Global Warming legislation that would raise taxes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americansforprosperity.org/files/Rokita_Todd.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-10-13 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120601132054/http://www.americansforprosperity.org/files/Rokita_Todd.pdf |archivedate=2012-06-01 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Legislation===\nOn April 2, 2014, Rokita introduced the [[Strengthening Education through Research Act (H.R. 4366; 113th Congress)]].<ref name=4366allactions>{{cite web|title=H.R. 4366 \u2013 All Actions|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/4366/all-actions/|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=6 May 2014}}</ref> The bill would amend and [[authorization bill|reauthorize]] the [[Education Sciences Reform Act of 2002]] and would authorize the [[appropriations bill (United States)|appropriation]] of $615 million for fiscal year 2015 and $3.8 billion over the 2015\u20132019 period to support federal educational research, statistical analysis, and other activities.<ref name=cbo4366>{{cite web|title=CBO \u2013 H.R. 4366|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45300|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=6 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRokita is a member of the Director's Circle of the Indiana Council for Economic Education, the state bar association, the Knights of Columbus, and the National Rifle Association. Rokita has also served as Chair of NASS's New Millennium Young Voters Summit of 2004, chair of the standing Voter Participation Committee and vice chair of the Securities Regulation Committee.<ref name=bio>{{cite web|url=http://rokita.house.gov/about-me/full-biography|title=Congressman Todd Rokita biodata|publisher=Rokita.house.gov|date=2012-01-27|accessdate=2013-10-21}}</ref>\n\nRokita formerly lived in [[Clermont, Indiana|Clermont]], an \"included town\" in [[Indianapolis]] under the [[Unigov]] system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://historycms.house.gov/WorkArea/DownloadAsset.aspx?id=15032389214 |title=OFFICIAL LIST OF MEMBERS |website=Historycms.house.gov |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref> However, the 2010 round of redistricting cut out the 4th's share of Indianapolis and [[Marion County, Indiana|Marion County]], leaving Rokita's home just 500 yards from the new 4th's eastern border.  Members of Congress are only required to live in the state they represent, though it is a strong convention that they live within their district's borders.  Rokita ran for reelection in 2012 from his home in Clermont,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nwitimes.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/article_21e1600b-ede7-54cf-989d-0fc4a139bd4e.html|title=Remap leaves U.S. Rep. Rokita outside his district|date=May 15, 2011|accessdate=May 21, 2011|work=[[The Times of Northwest Indiana|The Times]]|first=Dan|last=Carden}}</ref> but later bought a home near [[Brownsburg, Indiana|Brownsburg]], a western suburb of Indianapolis that is within the 4th.<ref name=bio/>\n\nRokita's oldest son, Teddy, suffers from [[Angelman syndrome]]. Rokita and his wife, Kathy, have been active in promoting awareness on the syndrome.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wthr.com/article/local-family-opens-door-little-known-syndrome |title=Local family opens the door on little-known syndrome - 13 WTHR Indianapolis |website=Wthr.com |date= |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref> They participate in and organize charity walks related to Angelman. He has cited his son's ailment in policy speeches.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?c4467126%2Frep-todd-rokitaangelman-syndrome |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-10-05 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006042617/https://www.c-span.org/video/?c4467126/rep-todd-rokitaangelman-syndrome |archivedate=2016-10-06 |df= }}</ref>\n\nA commercial-rated pilot, Rokita volunteers his time by flying people in need of non-emergency medical care to hospitals and clinics throughout the Midwest for treatment with organizations that include Veterans Airlift Command and Angel Flight.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://generalaviationnews.com/2011/10/19/congress-is-listening-at-least-one-member-is/ |title=Congress is listening\u2026 at least one member is \u2014 General Aviation News |website=Generalaviationnews.com |date=2011-10-19 |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wndu.com/content/news/Indiana-congressman-flies-veteran-for-free-384957371.html |title=Indiana congressman flies veteran for free |website=Wndu.com |date= |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bannergraphic.com/story/1969104.html |title=Local News: Congressman Rokita featured on Lincoln Day menu this Sunday (5/15/13) &#124; Greencastle Banner-Graphic |website=Bannergraphic.com |date=2013-05-15 |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>  He is a member of the Indiana chapter of the International Flying Farmers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flyergroup.com/news/election-profiles/article_30a9d050-6398-11e4-a48c-27a2b2540a5f.html |title=Election Profiles 1 &#124; News |website=Flyergroup.com |date=2014-11-03 |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://rokita.house.gov/ Congressman Todd Rokita] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.toddrokita.com Todd Rokita for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Indiana/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Todd_Rokita_%5BR-4%5D}}\n* {{C-SPAN|tedrokita}}\n{{CongLinks | congbio = R000592 | ballot = Todd_Rokita | nndb = 903/000266105 | votesmart = 34167 | govtrack = 412426 | opencong = 412426 | rollcall = 31051 | politifact = | fec = H0IN04170 | opensecrets = N00031741 | assets = todd-rokita | legistorm = 2753/Rep_Todd_Rokita_IN.html | followthemoney = 18679 | ontheissues = IN/Todd_Rokita.htm | congress = todd-rokita/2017 | worldcat = lccn-no2004-105297 | cspan = 61832 | imdb = | bloomberg = | nyt = | washpo = gIQAJQXZKP }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sue Anne Gilroy|Sue Gilroy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of St